{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_chinooksalmon_ver03/data/sn84020662/00414185940/1949051601/1258.xml":{"full_text":"WXLN AGAIN \"ON THE AIR\"\nFOR MORNING BROADCASTS\nPadio station WXLN, which has\nnot been broadcasting mornings\nfor the past few weeks due to op\nerational difficulties, resumed all\nmorning broadcasts this morning,\ndated Sgt. Johnnie Mock, who is\nui charge of the local station at\nMarks Air Force Base.\nProgram broadcasts will start\ndaily, except Sunday, at 7:00 a.m.\nSunday broadcasts will start at\n10:00 a.m. as before. \u201cSigning off\u201d\ntime will remain at 11:00 p.m. as\nluaial.\nXX. OF A. PROFESSOR\nGETS FELLOWSHIP\nSEAATLE, (JP) A fellowship\nfor advanced research by women\nhas been presented to Charlene\n('raft, formerly of Everett and\nhow an instructor at the Univer\nsity of Alaska, by the American\nAssociation of University Women.\nAn anthropology instruc tor,\nMias Craft, will make an archae\nlogical field trip in Upper Kusko\nTwo Million Draw\nU nemploy mentPay\n\nWASHINGTON, {/P)\u2014[The num\nber of workers drawing jobless in\nsurance pay fell off 57,000 last\nweek, the first drop in a month.\nThis decline brought the total\ndown to 1,980,000 during the week\nending May 7 as compared with\n2.037.000 for the preceding period.\nBut the federal security agency\nsaid Friday the number of newly\nlaid-off workers filing claims for\nunemployment compensation rose\nfrom 322,100 to 354,000 in the\nsame period.\nBefore last week\u2019s drop in job\nless payments, the agency noted\nthat for three weeks there had\nbeen a steady increase. Despite the\ndecline the May 7 total still was\n775.000 higher than in the same\nperiod last year.\nkwim this summer under the fel\nlowship. The area lies southeast of\nMt. McKinley National Park.\nAlaska Airlines\nAIR-RAIL\nSHIPMENTS\nANYWHERE\nFAST ECONOMICAL\nDOOR-TO-DOOR SERVICE\nV\nScheduled Freighter Service\nSeattle for Bering Sea\nFREIGHT\nSAILS RECEIVED SEATTLE\nM/\\r Ring Splice June 4 May 16 to June 1\nFor: Nome. Solomon. Golovin. St. Michael. Unalakleet.\nMosee Point. Savoonga and Gambell.\nFREIGHTER July 8 June 21 to July 5\nFor: Nome. Teller. Wales. Shishmaref. Deering.\nKeewalik and Kotsebue.\nORDER EARLY\u2014IT WILL INSURE phompt de\nLIVERY TO DOCK IN TIME FOR SCHEDULED SAILING\n9\nWXLN\nMonday, May 16, 1949\n5:00 p.m.\u2014Serenade\n5:15\u2014The Supper Club\n5:30\u2014Music of the Masters\n6:00\u2014Zeke Manners\n6:15\u2014Words With Music\n6:30\u2014The Man on the Street\n7:00\u2014News\n7:05\u2014Dennis Day\n7:30\u2014Hill Billy Hit Parade\n8:00\u2014News\n8:05\u2014Twenty Questions\n8:30\u2014Bing Crosby\n9:00\u2014You Asked For It\n10:00\u2014News\n10:05\u2014Sam Spade\n10:30\u2014Jack Carson\n11:00\u2014News\n11:05\u2014Sign Off\nTuesday. May 17. 1949\n7:00\u2014Melody Round Up\n7:15\u2014Morning Devotions\n7:30\u2014Musical Clock\n8:00\u2014News\n8:05\u2014Fred Waring\n8:30\u2014Record Shop\n9:00\u2014Morning Melodies\n9:15\u2014G I Jive\n9:30\u2014Jack Berch\n9:45\u2014Chiquita\n10:00\u2014Turntable Time\n10:30\u2014Heard At Home\n11:00\u2014Impressions In Melody\n11:30\u2014Album Music\n11:45\u2014Personal Album\nNoon\u2014V Disc Varieties\n12:30\u2014WXLN News\n12:45\u2014At Ease\n1:00\u2014Arond the World in History\n1:15\u2014Club Fifteen\n1:30\u2014You\u2019ll Be Surprised\n2:00\u2014Musical Varieties\n2:30\u2014Jubilee\n3:00\u2014Matinee Melodies\n4:00\u2014Remember\n4:15\u2014Today\u2019s American\n4:30\u2014One Night Stand\n5:00\u2014Baseball (Short Wave)\n6:00\u2014Zeke Manners\n6:15\u2014Words With Music\n6:30\u2014You Are There\n7:00\u2014News\n7:05\u2014Fibber McGee and Molly\n7:30\u2014Hill Billy Hit Parade\n8:00\u2014News\n8:05\u2014Red Skelton\n8:30\u2014Mail Call\n9:00\u2014You Asked For It\n10:00\u2014News\n10:05\u2014The Whistler\n10:30\u2014Music By Faith\n11:00\u2014News\n11:05\u2014Sign Off\nWednesday, May 18, 1949\n7:00 a.m.\u2014Melody Round-Up\nI 7:15\u2014Morning Devotions\n7:30\u2014Musical Clock\n8:00\u2014News\n8:05\u2014Fred Waring\n8:30\u2014Record Shop\n9:00\u2014Morning Melodies\n9:15\u2014G* I Jive\n9:30\u2014Jack Berch\n9:45\u2014Chiquita\n10:00\u2014Turntable Time\n10:30\u2014Heard At Home\n11:00\u2014Impressions In Melody\n11:30\u2014Album Music\n11:45\u2014Personal Album\nNoon\u2014V Disc Varieties\n12:30\u2014WXLN News\n12:45\u2014At Ease\n1:00\u2014Arond the World in History\n1:15\u2014Club Fifteen\n1:30\u2014You\u2019ll Be Surprised\n2:00\u2014Just Jazz\n2:30\u2014Westward Ho\n3:00\u2014Matinee Melodies\n4:00\u2014Solitary Singer\n4:15\u2014Today\u2019s American\n4:30\u2014One Night Stand\n5 00\u2014News\nMr. and Mrs. C. A. Bowers ar\nrived yesterday on the P.A.A. Mr.\nBower will do repair and installa\ntion work this summer for the\nStandard Oil Co., which plans to\nput in pumps this summer in ac\ncordance with permission granted\nthe company by the City Council\nduring the winter.\nDREAM\nTHEATER\n1 Show, Mon. and Tue., 7:30 p.m.\n\"CHEYENNE\"\nDennis Morgan Jane Wyman\nAlso \"Golden Hunch\"\n\nI Show, Wed. and Thur., 7:30 p.m,\n\"LIVING IN A BIG WAY\"\nGene Kelly Marie MacDonald\nAlso \"Studio Visiiy\"\nTax Committee\nPredicts Three\nDollar Deficit\n(Continued from Page One)\ncries today for more economy and\nmore taxes.\nThe estimate was made for the\nSenate-House tax committee by\nits staff of experts.\nThey forecast a \u201cmoderate\u201d!\nbusiness slump. They figured that\nin the fiscal year starting July 1\nit would result in cutting the gov\nernment\u2019s income by $2,100,000,\n000 and adding that much to the\n$900,(500,000 deficit predicted in\nPresident Truman\u2019s budget.\n\u201cThat,\u201d said House Democratic\nleader McCormack (Mass.), \u201cis all j\nthe more reason for increasing\ntaxes by $4,000,000,000, as Presi- j\ndent Truman repeatedly has sug-1\ngested.\u201d\nIn the Senate, however, Senator\nRussell (D.-Ga.) announced that j\nhe and some other Democratic\nmembers of the appropriations\ncommittee are drafting a bill to\nslice about $3,000,000,000 off fed\neral spending. Russell said their\nplans were started even before the\nreport of the tax experts was is\nsued. Senator Maybank (D.- S. C.) j\nsuggested the $5,580,000,000 Euro\npean aid program as a good place\nto cut.\nSenator McKellar (D.-Tenn.),\nchairman of the Appropriations\ncommittee, said he would \u201crather\ncut government exenditures than\nraise taxes.\u201d\nChairman Doughton (D.-N. C.)\nsaid he doesn\u2019t want to be put in\nthe position of warring with the\nPresident. And he wouldn\u2019t fore\ncast what his committee will do.\nBut he said his own position is\nwell known.\n\u201cWhen it looks like we are go\ning to spend more money than\nwe\u2019ve got,\u201d he said, \u201ceconomy is\nin order and important.\u201d\nThere are three courses open,\nDoughton said:\n1. Cut appropriations; 2. Boost\ntaxes; 3. Resort to \u201cdeficit financ\ning,\u201d which means going deeper\ninto debt to pay for government\nWill Introduce Air\nLines Subsidy Bill\nWASHINGTON, (/P)\u2014Chairman\nEdwin C. Johnson (D.-Colo.) said\ntoday the Senate commerce com\nmittee is working out a bill to sep\narate airline subsidy from actual\nmail pay,\n\u201cThe bill will authorize funds\nfor a complete study by the civil\naeronautics board (CAB) of sep\naration of a compensatory mail\npay and subsidy which we hope\nwill result in a formula for getting\nthe job done,\u201d Johnson said.\nThe committee is now conduct\ning an investigation into airline fi\nnances and operating efficiency.\nJohnson says it wants to know\n\u2022why so many lines are operating\nin the red.\nJohnson told a reporter the com\nmittee bill ought to be ready this\nweek. He predicted that it would\nbe non-controversial and could be\npassed by th^Senate as routine,\nwithout debate.\nThe study, he said, will require\nseveral months and no estimate of\nthe cost has been made.\nJohnson has insisted that a sep\naration of compensation and sub\nsidy in the mail pay is essential to\nobtaining a true picture of the fi\nnancial condition and operating ef\nficiency of the air carriers.\nAir mail rates now are set by\nthe CAB and paid for by* the post\noffice department. The treasury\npost office spending bill, approved\nby the Senate last week, con\ntained an $87,061,000 item for pay\nment of the costs of carrying mail\nand subsidy to the commercial\nairlines.\nMrs. W. Nay. of the Alaska Air\nlines returned home Saturday on\na special flight of the Alaska Air\nlines which brought in a load of\nmail, freight and fresh meat. She\nhas been in Anchorage for about\na week.\nI expenses.\nAnd. he said, the responsibility\nfor the choice rests on all the\nmembers of Congress, \u201cnot on Bob\nDoughton and not on Harry Tru\nman.\u201d\nBEAUTIFUL\nMARTEN NECKPIECES\nMINK NECKPIECES\nSILVER FOX NECKPIECES\nGRAY FOX NECKPIECES\nf\n-Also\ni 5\nA Fine Assortment of Exceptionally\nLow-Priced Raw Skins\ns\n11","height":"27400","width":"20616"}}
